{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"acc70bf7-a079-495d-a547-17d6c5938c51","content":"The project doesn't exist yet at that path. But here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport (the standard for local tools):\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command`/`args`** — runs `dotnet run` pointing at your `.csproj`.\n- For a **published** build, use `\"command\": \"dotnet\"` with `\"args\": [\"path/to/MyMcpServer.dll\"]`, or point directly to the executable.\n- If your server uses **SSE/HTTP** instead, use `\"type\": \"sse\"` with a `\"url\"` field.\n\nAfter saving, restart the Copilot language server or reload VS Code. Your MCP tools will then appear in agent mode.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"df6f1dc1-f9d4-40e7-8ea6-1bd64281e835","outputTokens":300,"requestId":"7010:2E7D56:1428B8F:175C8A2:69EC1167"},"id":"e260e8e9-302a-4a5b-b545-e9ec10161cd3","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:57:19.200Z","parentId":"b9725d6c-2013-47c0-9c79-a236d99ffdd7"}
